title: Serde Fragment to json
feat: detect commit conflicts
body:
Closes #1103

This PR add commit conflict detection. The protocol is clarified to specify how conflicts are detected, and which commit mechanisms should be preferred.

A new API is added in Python and Rust to provide a custom locking implementation for when the store doesn't natively support atomic commits (specifically, AWS S3). Note that is it not recommended to use this for stores that do support atomic commits, since it's also important to make sure all writers are using the same commit mechanism.

Now, by default, most stores commit by performing a replace-if-not-exist on the new manifest file path. S3 just performs this naively, but we log a warning to let users know this won't be robust when there are concurrent writers.

title: Optimize block size based on query type
body:
We should benchmark the latency we get from different block sizes as well as how much concurrency we can get from different object stores.

Because of request rate limits, there's likely to be a tradeoff between latency (better with smaller block sizes) and throughput (better with larger block sizes). Depending on the type of query, we may want to optimize for one or the other. For example, a KNN query will likely want to optimize for latency. Whereas a OLAP scan will want to optimize for throughput. We should be able to provide good automatic defaults based on the query plan. Of course, the user can always input their own settings as needed.

body:
This PR is meant to improve performance where we are (1) scanning a lot of data and (2) performing many `take()` calls.

To improve the scan performance, we set a new default for object stores to have a higher block size. To make this easier for users, the default batch size has been pegged to the block size. Otherwise users would have to tune both in tandem. (They still can of course, and this PR exposes the `batch_size` parameter to Python users.) We also change the batch reading logic to read columns in parallel.

To improve the take performance, we add a new caching layer which caches various metadata from a file, such as the file metadata, the page table, and the deletion vector contents.

title: Collect page-level statistics on write
body:
As we write out pages, collect the min value, max value, num values, and null count for each page.

## Requirements

* The statistics should be stored in Arrow arrays. The format is described by #1047.
* Which columns statistics are collected for should be configurable. By default we can do all columns, but there may be use cases where we only want to care about certain columns.
* For binary/string columns, we should only collect truncated values for min and max. The rules for handling them are also outlined in #1047.
* Note that we will likely want to be able to use the statistics to dynamically select encodings page-by-page in the future, so the statistics collection should be positioned to make that possible.
* Should handle nested fields in structs.

Statistics for list columns may be left out-of-scope for now, since it's unclear in which situations they will be useful. (It's meaningless for most tensors, but can be useful for some non-tensor columns.)

title: wip: describe stats format
body:
This PR introduces format changes for statistics and "fragment manifests".

## Statistics

Statistics are added at page and fragment level to lay the foundation for "implicit partitioning". Writers will be able to split and sort files as they see fit, and then the layout will be surfaced to readers through the fragment-level statistics. This means any innovation in table partitioning and ordering will be backwards compatible for all readers that support stats.

## Fragment manifests

Currently the list of fragments are stored inside the manifest protobuf message. This will likely not scale well to extremely large tables that have millions of fragments, since the entire messages needs to be deserialized together. Instead, fragment manifests allow the fragment metadata to be stored in a columnar format and even split across several files. When combined with statistics, this will allow data skipping within the metadata, making selective scans much faster in large tables.

We could defer this piece until after doing statistics, but that means adding stats to the protobuf format *and* then to the fragment manifest format, creating an intermediate format we'll have to support in the long term. I think it's best we avoid that.

Closes #1046

title: Partial support for pre-filtering
body:
Ideally we would support the combined filtering via streaming ANN results. However, there still a non-trivial amount of performance work and uncertainty on the design.

In the mean time, one way to achieve partial support is to use KNN instead of ANN. The use case here is that oftentimes filters will reduce the search space down to O(1e3) to O(1e4) vectors, which our KNN implementation can handle within say 25ms.

This would look like KNN -> Filter -> Scan.

Work involved:

1. API (how would user indicate pre vs post filtering?)
2. New IO path
3. Can we add some guardrails so in the event that the filter returns a very large resultset (eg O(1e6+)), we don't just feed it to the KNN blindly?

title: allow object store wrapper as part of dataset construction param
body:
## Why?

We need a way to inject a customized `object_store::ObjectStore` into `lance::io::object_store::ObjectStore`.

We could go full java-style dependency injection and take a pre-constructed `object_store::ObjectStore`. But that seems to be way too big of a refactor. The refactor would probably break the assumptions built into `base_path` easily. This PR add a way to hook into `lance::io::object_store::ObjectStore` construction and allow callers to wrap the inner `object_store::ObjectStore` with custom logic.

## What?

* added a `WrappingObjectStore` trait which is a hook called after we construct `object_store::ObjectStore` from the uri provided.
* added `ObjectStoreParams` and `from_uri_and_params`
